<TEXT>
<P>
Re Marilyn Brown's Aug. 13 letter condemning the ad for the film "Parenthood" 
that depicts Steve Martin holding two children upside down by their ankles: Oh, 
thank the Lord! Yet another repressed individual with a pen and a stamp has 
done us a public service, demanding this ad be withdrawn because of the 
potential hazards of holding a child upside down. 
</P>
<P>
Let me finish the list: If Rhett really held Scarlett as he did in the "Gone 
With the Wind" poster, she would have developed scoliosis; if Robin Williams 
had been dropped as he was being carried in the ad for "Dead Poet's Society," 
he could have knocked out a tooth; if Dennis Quaid had fallen off the piano in 
"Great Balls of Fire" he could have suffered a brain aneurysm, causing him to 
dress like a giant bat and fight crime. 
</P>
<P>
It's time to stop dropping our mouths over rock lyrics, to stop writing 
complaints to "Married With Children," to stop being so uptight. As 
"Parenthood" suggests, roll with life; lighten up. 
</P>
<P>
I remember when my father used to hold me upside down -- and I smile. 
</P>
<P>
BRIAN S. DAY 
</P>
<P>
Temple City 
</P>
</TEXT>
